            {"role": "user", "content": "Client: 28M, charged with Possession of Controlled Substance (cocaine, 3.2g), 4th degree felony. Arresting officer says he smelled marijuana coming from a stopped vehicle, conducted a search, and found cocaine in the glove box. No warrant. Client was the passenger. State: Ohio."},
            {"role": "assistant", "content": "## Charges Analyzed\n- **Possession of Controlled Substance (Cocaine)** — Ohio R.C. § 2925.11(A), Schedule II. 3.2g = 4th degree felony (less than 5g).\n\n## Defense Strategies\n\n**Theory: Fourth Amendment Suppression — Unlawful Search**\n- **Basis:** The officer claims marijuana odor as probable cause for a warrantless vehicle search. However, Ohio legalized recreational marijuana in 2023 (Issue 2). The smell of marijuana alone may no longer establish probable cause in Ohio post-legalization. *State v. Yanowitz* (2024) and related rulings are unsettled — this is an active suppression argument.\n- **Strength:** Strong. File a motion to suppress immediately.\n\n**Theory: Lack of Possession — Passenger Status**\n- **Basis:** Client was a passenger, not the driver. The cocaine was in the glove box. Constructive possession requires the state to prove the client had knowledge of and control over the contraband. In a multi-occupant vehicle, this is a contested element.\n- **Strength:** Moderate. The state must prove dominion and control, not just proximity.\n\n**Theory: Chain of Custody / Lab Certification**\n- **Basis:** The substance must be independently tested and certified. Challenge the lab analyst's qualifications and the chain of custody from seizure to testing.\n- **Strength:** Moderate as a stand-alone, strong as a combined challenge.\n\n## Constitutional Issues\n\n⚠ **CONSTITUTIONAL CONCERN — 4th Amendment (U.S. Const. amend. IV; Ohio Const. Art. I § 14)**\nThe warrantless vehicle search predicated solely on marijuana odor may lack probable cause under Ohio's post-legalization framework. If the search was unlawful, all evidence recovered — including the cocaine — is subject to suppression under the exclusionary rule (*Mapp v. Ohio*, 367 U.S. 643 (1961); *fruit of the poisonous tree* doctrine, *Wong Sun v. United States*, 371 U.S. 471 (1963)).\n\n⚠ **CONSTITUTIONAL CONCERN — 14th Amendment (Equal Protection)**\nIf similarly situated drivers are not searched under identical circumstances, raise selective enforcement.\n\n## Evidentiary Weaknesses\n\n- Marijuana odor probable cause is legally unsettled in Ohio post-Issue 2 — prosecution must overcome this threshold issue before any evidence is admissible\n- No forensic evidence placing client's fingerprints or DNA on the contraband or glove box\n- Client's status as passenger, not owner/driver, weakens constructive possession\n- No evidence client knew the glove box contained cocaine\n- Was the vehicle searched incident to arrest, or before arrest? Sequence matters for *Arizona v. Gant*, 556 U.S. 332 (2009) analysis\n\n## Brady/Giglio Obligations\n\nRequest the following in discovery:\n- Officer's complete disciplinary record and prior suppression hearing losses (impeachment under *Giglio v. United States*, 405 U.S. 150 (1972))\n- Any prior complaints of unlawful searches by this officer\n- Lab results, chain of custody documentation, and analyst certification\n- Dash and body camera footage\n- Any statements or deals offered to the driver\n\n## Mitigating Factors\n\n- First offense or minimal record → diversion eligibility under Ohio's Intervention in Lieu of Conviction (ILC), R.C. § 2951.041\n- Cocaine amount is below trafficking threshold — possession only\n- Passenger status (not the driver/owner)\n- Employment, family ties, community support for sentencing variance\n\n## Recommended Next Steps\n\n1. **File a Motion to Suppress** — challenge the lawfulness of the search under the 4th Amendment; this is the dispositive issue\n2. **Request full discovery** — dash cam, body cam, officer notes, lab reports, chain of custody\n3. **Investigate marijuana odor doctrine in Ohio** — cite post-legalization authority and distinguish cases decided before Issue 2\n4. **Evaluate ILC eligibility** — if suppression fails, diversion may avoid a felony conviction entirely\n5. **Challenge constructive possession** — prepare jury instruction on knowledge and control if case proceeds to trial"},
