            {"role": "assistant", "content": "## Charges Analyzed\n- **DUI Less Safe / DUI Per Se** — O.C.G.A. § 40-6-391. BAC 0.09% = per se violation (≥ 0.08%). First offense misdemeanor.\n\n## Defense Strategies\n\n**Theory: Unlawful Traffic Stop — Lack of Reasonable Articulable Suspicion**\n- **Basis:** 'Weaving within a lane' without crossing lane lines is not per se a traffic violation in Georgia. *Elliott v. State*, 305 Ga. App. 290 (2010): weaving within a lane, standing alone, may be insufficient for a stop. If the stop was unlawful, all evidence including the BAC is suppressible.\n- **Strength:** Strong — this is the threshold issue.\n\n**Theory: Breathalyzer Reliability**\n- **Basis:** BAC of 0.09% is marginally above the legal limit. Challenge: (1) calibration and maintenance records of the Intoxilyzer device; (2) officer's certification to operate the device; (3) whether the 20-minute observation period was properly maintained before the test; (4) mouth alcohol contamination.\n- **Strength:** Moderate to Strong. A 0.01% margin leaves meaningful room to attack reliability.\n\n**Theory: Field Sobriety Test Performance as Exculpatory**\n- **Basis:** Client passed all field sobriety tests. This is affirmative evidence of sobriety and undermines the 'less safe' prong. Use this offensively at trial.\n- **Strength:** Strong for the less safe charge; does not defeat per se unless BAC is excluded.\n\n## Constitutional Issues\n\n⚠ **CONSTITUTIONAL CONCERN — 4th Amendment**\nIf 'weaving within lane' was the sole basis for the stop, the stop may lack reasonable articulable suspicion under *Terry v. Ohio*, 392 U.S. 1 (1968). Suppression of all evidence — including the breathalyzer result — would follow under the exclusionary rule.\n\n## Evidentiary Weaknesses\n\n- BAC is only 0.01% above the legal limit — within breathalyzer margin of error (±0.005 per NHTSA)\n- Passed all FSTs — cuts directly against less safe impairment\n- 'Weaving within lane' is legally insufficient for a stop under Georgia case law\n- Prosecution must prove the Intoxilyzer 9000 was properly calibrated, maintained, and operated by a certified officer\n- Rising BAC defense: if client consumed alcohol shortly before driving, BAC may have been below 0.08% while operating the vehicle and risen by test time\n\n## Brady/Giglio Obligations\n\n- Dash cam footage of the driving behavior (critical for stop validity)\n- Intoxilyzer 9000 calibration logs, maintenance records, and certification records for the specific unit used\n- Officer's Intoxilyzer certification and training records\n- Any prior suppression rulings against this officer\n\n## Mitigating Factors\n\n- First offense → Georgia First Offender Act (O.C.G.A. § 42-8-60) may apply, avoiding a conviction record if program is completed\n- DUI Alcohol Risk Reduction Program completion reduces license suspension\n- Cooperative with law enforcement, no accident, no injury\n- Marginal BAC argues against serious impairment\n\n## Recommended Next Steps\n\n1. **File Motion to Suppress** — challenge the traffic stop; if granted, the case ends\n2. **Subpoena all Intoxilyzer records** — calibration, maintenance, officer certification\n3. **Obtain and preserve dash cam footage** — essential to evaluate the 'weaving' claim\n4. **Evaluate First Offender Act** — if suppression fails, this avoids a permanent DUI conviction\n5. **Consider rising BAC expert** — if timeline supports it, a toxicologist can testify that BAC was below 0.08% while driving"},
