            {"role": "user", "content": "Client: 19M, charged with Robbery in the Second Degree (New York Penal Law § 160.10). Complaining witness identified him in a police station show-up 45 minutes after the incident. No other evidence. No weapon recovered. Client has an alibi — he was at work — but his employer is reluctant to provide records."},
            {"role": "assistant", "content": "## Charges Analyzed\n- **Robbery Second Degree** — NY PL § 160.10. Class C violent felony. Requires forcible stealing plus an aggravating factor (aided by another, causes injury, or displays what appears to be a firearm). Identify which subsection is charged.\n\n## Defense Strategies\n\n**Theory: Eyewitness Misidentification**\n- **Basis:** The identification was a show-up — a one-person procedure inherently suggestive. The complaining witness saw one person presented by police 45 minutes post-incident, under stress, without lineup safeguards. Misidentification is the leading cause of wrongful convictions (National Registry of Exonerations). Request a Wade hearing (*United States v. Wade*, 388 U.S. 218 (1967)) to challenge the admissibility of the identification.\n- **Strength:** Strong. Show-ups are disfavored and subject to suppression if unnecessarily suggestive and unreliable under the *Manson v. Brathwaite* totality framework.\n\n**Theory: Alibi Defense**\n- **Basis:** Client was at work at the time of the offense. Even with a reluctant employer, pursue: (1) time-clock records, (2) security camera footage, (3) co-worker testimony, (4) electronic records (badge swipes, login timestamps, payroll data). Subpoena if necessary — employers cannot legally obstruct a criminal defense subpoena.\n- **Strength:** Strong if records are obtained.\n\n**Theory: Insufficient Evidence — Element Failure**\n- **Basis:** If no weapon was recovered and no injury occurred, the prosecution must prove the aggravating element beyond a reasonable doubt. A bare show-up identification with no corroborating evidence may be insufficient.\n- **Strength:** Moderate — depends on the specific subsection charged.\n\n## Constitutional Issues\n\n⚠ **CONSTITUTIONAL CONCERN — Due Process (14th Amendment)**\nA show-up identification procedure is inherently suggestive. Under *Neil v. Biggers*, 409 U.S. 188 (1972), and *Manson v. Brathwaite*, 432 U.S. 98 (1977), the court must evaluate whether the procedure was unnecessarily suggestive and, if so, whether the identification is nonetheless reliable under the totality of circumstances. File a Wade hearing motion immediately — the identification may be suppressed entirely.\n\n⚠ **CONSTITUTIONAL CONCERN — 6th Amendment (Right to Compulsory Process)**\nIf the employer refuses to cooperate, serve a trial subpoena for records and witnesses under CPLR Article 23. The 6th Amendment guarantees the right to compel witnesses and documents in the defendant's favor.\n\n## Evidentiary Weaknesses\n\n- Single eyewitness, show-up procedure — no lineup, no photo array\n- Stress, lighting, cross-racial identification factors affect reliability (request expert on eyewitness memory)\n- No physical evidence linking client to the crime\n- No weapon recovered\n- No corroborating witnesses\n- 45 minutes elapsed — memory degradation and suggestibility increase with time and police interaction\n\n## Brady/Giglio Obligations\n\n- All police reports describing the show-up procedure (lighting, instructions given to witness, officer presence during identification)\n- Any prior inconsistent descriptions by the complaining witness\n- Any other suspects considered and cleared\n- Officer's prior disciplinary record, including any misconduct related to identification procedures\n- Any video footage from the show-up location\n\n## Mitigating Factors\n\n- Age 19 — youthful offender treatment may apply (NY CPL § 720.10) if no prior felony, avoiding a permanent felony record\n- No weapon, no injury — bottom of the range if convicted\n- First offense → argue for alternatives to incarceration\n\n## Recommended Next Steps\n\n1. **File a Wade Hearing motion** — challenge the show-up identification before trial\n2. **Serve subpoenas immediately** — employer records, time-clock data, surveillance footage; do not wait for voluntary cooperation\n3. **Retain an eyewitness expert** — testimony on show-up unreliability is admissible in New York\n4. **Evaluate Youthful Offender application** — if client qualifies, pursue aggressively\n5. **Identify and interview co-workers** — corroborate alibi through multiple witnesses, not just records"},
