            {"role": "system", "content": SYSTEM_PROMPT},
            {"role": "user", "content": "What is the Brady rule and what must the prosecution disclose?"},
            {"role": "assistant", "content": "## The Brady Rule\n\n**Source:** *Brady v. Maryland*, 373 U.S. 83 (1963) (U.S. Supreme Court)\n\n**The Rule:** The Due Process Clause of the 14th Amendment requires the prosecution to disclose evidence that is:\n1. **Favorable to the accused** (exculpatory or impeaching), AND\n2. **Material** — meaning there is a reasonable probability that, had the evidence been disclosed, the outcome of the trial would have been different (*Strickler v. Greene*, 527 U.S. 263 (1999))\n\nBrady applies whether or not the defense requests the material.\n\n---\n\n## Giglio — Impeachment Evidence\n\n**Source:** *Giglio v. United States*, 405 U.S. 150 (1972)\n\nExtends Brady to **impeachment evidence** — material that undermines the credibility of prosecution witnesses, including:\n- Deals, promises, or benefits offered to cooperating witnesses\n- Prior inconsistent statements by witnesses\n- Criminal records of government witnesses\n- Pending charges against witnesses who are cooperating\n\n---\n\n## Categories of Brady/Giglio Material\n\n**Exculpatory (Brady):**\n- Evidence pointing to another suspect\n- Witness statements inconsistent with guilt\n- Physical evidence inconsistent with the charged crime\n- Evidence negating an element of the offense (intent, identity, etc.)\n- Evidence of a victim's prior false accusations\n- Lab results that do not inculpate the defendant\n\n**Impeachment (Giglio):**\n- Promises of leniency or immunity to cooperating witnesses\n- Prior criminal convictions of witnesses\n- Known bias or motive of witnesses\n- Officer disciplinary records for dishonesty or misconduct (*See: Laurie List / Brady List obligations*)\n- Prior inconsistent statements by prosecution witnesses\n\n---\n\n## Materiality Standard\n\n*United States v. Bagley*, 473 U.S. 667 (1985): Evidence is material if there is a 'reasonable probability' — not a certainty — that disclosure would have produced a different result. The standard is not whether the defendant would have been acquitted, but whether confidence in the verdict is undermined.\n\n---\n\n## Practical Notes for Defense Counsel\n\n- **Request broadly and in writing** — put the prosecution on notice of specific categories\n- **Timing:** Brady material must be disclosed in time for effective use at trial (*Cone v. Bell*, 556 U.S. 449 (2009))\n- **Remedy for violation:** Suppression of the conviction; new trial; dismissal in egregious cases\n- **Do not rely on the prosecution's judgment** — file specific discovery requests covering every Brady/Giglio category\n- **Officer credibility files:** Many jurisdictions maintain 'Laurie Lists' or 'Brady Lists' of officers with credibility issues — subpoena these directly from the prosecution or police department"},
