            {"role": "assistant", "content": "## Charges Analyzed\n- **Felony Murder — First Degree** — California Penal Code § 189. As amended by SB 1437 (2019) and AB 333 (2021), California significantly reformed felony murder liability.\n\n## Defense Strategies\n\n**Theory: SB 1437 / AB 333 — Felony Murder Reform**\n- **Basis:** California's felony murder rule was fundamentally reformed by SB 1437 (2019, codified at PC § 188-189). Under current law, a person is NOT liable for felony murder unless they:\n  1. Were the actual killer, OR\n  2. With intent to kill, aided and abetted the actual killer, OR\n  3. Were a **major participant** in the underlying felony AND acted with **reckless indifference to human life**\n- Client served as a lookout without knowledge of the weapon. This directly contests 'major participant' and 'reckless indifference' — the two elements the prosecution must now prove beyond a reasonable doubt.\n- **Strength:** Very Strong. This is the central defense.\n\n**Theory: Lack of Knowledge of Weapon — Reckless Indifference**\n- **Basis:** *People v. Banks*, 61 Cal.4th 788 (2015) and *People v. Clark*, 63 Cal.4th 522 (2016) define 'reckless indifference to human life' — client must have been subjectively aware her conduct created a grave risk of death. Not knowing a co-defendant had a weapon is direct evidence against reckless indifference.\n- **Strength:** Strong.\n\n**Theory: Not a Major Participant**\n- **Basis:** Under *Banks*, factors for 'major participant' include: role in planning, supplying weapons, presence at the scene, awareness of danger, actions during the crime, and actions after the killing. A lookout who did not know about the weapon scores low on nearly every factor.\n- **Strength:** Strong.\n\n## Constitutional Issues\n\n⚠ **CONSTITUTIONAL CONCERN — 8th Amendment (Disproportionate Punishment)**\nImposing a felony murder conviction — and potentially life imprisonment — on a participant who did not know a weapon was present and had no intent to kill may implicate *Enmund v. Florida*, 458 U.S. 782 (1982) and *Tison v. Arizona*, 481 U.S. 137 (1987): the 8th Amendment prohibits death or disproportionate punishment for felony murder without proof of culpable mental state.\n\n⚠ **CONSTITUTIONAL CONCERN — Due Process**\nRetroactive application of the old felony murder rule to conduct after SB 1437's effective date (January 1, 2019) would be unconstitutional. Confirm date of offense.\n\n## Evidentiary Weaknesses\n\n- Client had no knowledge of the weapon — negates reckless indifference\n- Lookout role places her outside the immediate crime scene — supports 'not major participant'\n- No evidence of planning, no prior agreement to use violence\n- The prosecution must affirmatively prove each Banks/Clark factor beyond a reasonable doubt\n- Co-defendant's criminal history and propensity for violence (unknown to client) is relevant to reckless indifference\n\n## Brady/Giglio Obligations\n\n- Any statements by co-defendant confirming client did not know about the weapon\n- Any deals offered to co-defendant in exchange for testimony\n- Full investigation file including initial police assessments of each participant's role\n- Any recorded statements by client showing lack of knowledge or intent\n\n## Mitigating Factors\n\n- Age 22, potentially first offense\n- Minimal role — lookout only\n- No intent to kill, no knowledge of weapon\n- California's Youth Offender Parole Hearing provisions (PC § 3051) if under 26 at time of offense\n- Strong candidate for PC § 1172.6 resentencing petition if convicted under old law\n\n## Recommended Next Steps\n\n1. **Challenge major participant and reckless indifference elements** under *Banks* and *Clark* at both preliminary hearing and trial\n2. **Move to sever** from co-defendant — joint trial prejudices client with the shooter's conduct\n3. **Lock in co-defendant's testimony** that client did not know about the weapon — before any plea deal changes the story\n4. **If already convicted under old law**, file a PC § 1172.6 resentencing petition — SB 1437 applies retroactively\n5. **Investigate client's specific role** in minute detail — every fact that distances her from planning or weapon knowledge strengthens the Banks/Clark defense"},
