            {"role": "user", "content": "Client invoked his right to counsel during a custodial interrogation. The detective left, came back 2 hours later, and resumed questioning without counsel present. Client eventually made incriminating statements. Can these statements be suppressed?"},
            {"role": "assistant", "content": "## Issue: Post-Invocation Interrogation — 5th and 6th Amendment\n\n## Answer: Yes — Strong Grounds for Suppression\n\n### Fifth Amendment Analysis — *Edwards v. Arizona*\n\n**Rule:** Once a suspect invokes the right to counsel during custodial interrogation, all interrogation must **cease immediately**. Police may not reinitiate interrogation unless:\n1. Counsel has been made available to the suspect, OR\n2. The suspect himself voluntarily reinitiates communication\n\n**Source:** *Edwards v. Arizona*, 451 U.S. 477 (1981) — one of the most protective bright-line rules in criminal procedure.\n\n**Applied here:** The detective ceased interrogation (correct) but returned 2 hours later and resumed questioning without counsel present and without the client voluntarily reinitiating. This is a textbook *Edwards* violation. The incriminating statements are presumptively inadmissible.\n\n### Additional Authority\n\n- *Minnick v. Mississippi*, 498 U.S. 146 (1990): The right to counsel under *Edwards* is not satisfied by a single consultation with an attorney — interrogation may not resume even after the suspect has spoken with counsel unless the suspect reinitiates.\n- *Maryland v. Shatzer*, 559 U.S. 98 (2010): Established a 14-day break-in-custody exception — if a suspect is released from custody for 14+ days before recontact, *Edwards* protections restart. A 2-hour gap within continuous custody does not trigger this exception.\n\n### Sixth Amendment Analysis\n\nIf formal proceedings had been initiated (indictment, arraignment, or first appearance) before the interrogation, the 6th Amendment right to counsel attaches independently (*Massiah v. United States*, 377 U.S. 201 (1964)). Deliberate elicitation of statements outside counsel's presence after attachment is a separate and independent constitutional violation.\n\n### Voluntariness\n\nEven if the court finds a technical exception, statements made after an *Edwards* violation carry a strong argument of involuntariness under the totality of circumstances (*Colorado v. Connelly*, 479 U.S. 157 (1986) — but note the voluntariness standard is separate from *Edwards*).\n\n## Motion to Suppress — Key Arguments\n\n1. Client unambiguously invoked the right to counsel (confirm exact words — *Berghuis v. Thompkins*, 560 U.S. 370 (2010) requires an unambiguous invocation)\n2. Police reinitiated interrogation without counsel present\n3. Client did not voluntarily reinitiate communication\n4. No *Shatzer* exception applies — continuous custody, 2-hour gap only\n5. All statements and derivative evidence must be suppressed\n\n## What to Gather\n\n- Full interrogation recording (audio and video)\n- Written or oral invocation language — document the exact words used\n- Custody timeline — was there any break in custody?\n- Any written Miranda waiver forms\n- Booking and transport records"},
